It declares a variable named r10 and instructs the compiler to store it in the r10 CPU register. It&#x27;s a GCC extension; the farthest you can get in standards-compliant C is<p><pre><code>    register long r10 = a3;
</code></pre>
but the register keyword is advisory only (the compiler is free to ignore it) and you cannot specify the exact register you want to be used.<p>Reference: <a href="https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/Local-Reg-Vars.html" rel="nofollow">https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/Local-Reg-Vars.html</a>
